            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mateo Reyes is a product of San Francisco\u2019s fog-laced western edge. Raised in the Outer Sunset, his childhood was a blend of his mother\u2019s Mexican heritage and his father's Filipino roots\u2014a home filled with the scent of adobo and fresh tortillas. His father, a union carpenter, and his mother, a hotel housekeeper, instilled in him a powerful work ethic. They had modest dreams for Mateo: a city college degree, maybe a stable office job, a life slightly easier than their own.\n\nThat path diverged sharply when Mateo was 18. A serious on-the-job injury forced his father into early retirement, and the family\u2019s financial stability vanished overnight. College was no longer an option. Putting his family first, Mateo took the civil service exam and landed a position as a Mail Processing Clerk for the USPS. The graveyard shift was grueling, but the pay was steady, the benefits secure. It was a sacrifice he made without a second thought.\n\nNow 30, Mateo\u2019s life is governed by a rhythm alien to most of the city. His day begins when others\u2019 are ending. He boards the L Taraval MUNI for the long ride to the massive distribution center, the city transforming from sleepy neighborhoods to industrial landscapes. Inside, he is part of the city\u2019s unseen pulse, ensuring its messages and packages keep moving.\n\nHe lives in a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond with two roommates. His social life is built around his nocturnal schedule\u2014late-night diners with his long-term girlfriend, Chloe, a hospital nurse, and weekend hikes at Lands End with a tight-knit group of friends from high school. He is deeply connected to a San Francisco that exists beyond tech campuses and tourist traps.\n\nMateo doesn't dream of startups or fame. His aspirations are grounded and sincere: to save enough for a down payment on a small condo, maybe in Daly City; to eventually earn a supervisor position at the post office; and to one day take his parents on a trip to see family in both Mexico and the Philippines. He is the quiet engine of the city, a testament to the resilience and dedication that keeps San Francisco running long after the sun has set."
        },
